llm_prompt_template:
You are a precise data extraction assistant. Extract structured JSON from an analytical prose text about intellectual evolution tactics.

Return a JSON object with this EXACT structure:

{
  "tactics_detected": [
    {
      "tactic_id": "t_1",
      "tactic_type": "<one of: conceptual_recycling, strategic_ambiguity, audience_bridging, vocabulary_migration, methodological_shift, position_reversal, scope_expansion, narrative_reframing, authority_leveraging, selective_citation>",
      "tactic_name": "<descriptive name for this specific tactic instance>",
      "description": "<2-3 sentence description of the tactic and how it manifests>",
      "idea_ids_involved": ["<idea IDs if mentioned>"],
      "prior_work_references": [
        {"work_title": "<title>", "relevant_quote": "<quote if available>"}
      ],
      "current_work_evidence": [
        {"quote": "<evidence from current work>", "location": "<chapter/section if mentioned>"}
      ],
      "severity": "<one of: major, moderate, minor>",
      "assessment": "<brief analytical assessment of this tactic's significance>"
    }
  ],
  "tactic_patterns": {
    "most_frequent_tactic": "<tactic_type that appears most often>",
    "tactic_distribution": {"<tactic_type>": "<count>"},
    "pattern_narrative": "<2-3 paragraph narrative about the overall tactical patterns>"
  }
}

RULES:
1. Return ONLY JSON — no markdown fences, no commentary
2. Use sequential IDs: t_1, t_2, ...
3. tactic_type MUST be one of the 10 listed values
4. severity: major = fundamentally shapes the argument, moderate = notable pattern, minor = occasional occurrence
5. Capture ALL tactics mentioned in the prose, not just the first few
6. The pattern_narrative should synthesize what the tactic distribution reveals about the author
